86–1434","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1404":"1404","about 1360":"about 1360","22 November 1404":"22 November 1404","1434":"1434","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1386":"1386","1385":"1385","1363":"1363","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","about 1385":"about 1385","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Woodlands, Dorset, England":"Woodlands, Dorset, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Buckingham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckingham, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tregos","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Colombia): possibly a nickname from <i>trejo</i>, meaning ‘daring, bold’, an Americanism in Spanish."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Tregos was born about 1360, in Cornwall, England. She married John Frome in 1382, in Buckingham, Buckinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in 1420, in Sussex, England, at the age of 61."},"et":{"about 1360–1420":"umbes 1360–1420","1363–1404":"1363–1404","1385–1442":"1385–1442","1386–1434":"1386–1434","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1404":"1404","about 1360":"umbes 1360","22 November 1404":"22. november 1404","1434":"1434","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1386":"1386","1385":"1385","1363":"1363","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","about 1385":"umbes 1385","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Woodlands, Dorset, England":"Woodlands, Dor